{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:186","names":{"en":"Sultans of Brunei","tr":"Brunei Sultanları","ar":"Salātīn Brūnāy"},"country":["BN","ID"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"186","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sultans of Brunei","parent_tribe":"Brunei Malay hanedanı","ethnic_origin":"Malay","capital":"Brunei (Bandar Seri Begawan)","region_primary":"Brunei (Borneo kuzeybatısı)","regions_all":"Brunei Darüsselam; Borneo kuzeybatı kıyısı; Sulu (geçici); Sabah/Sarawak (tarihi)","geographic_zone":"Güneydoğu Asya","predecessor":"Hindu-Budist Brunei beylikleri","successor":"— (Brunei Darüsselam bağımsız devlet, 1984)","government_type":"Sultanlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sultans of Brunei were a Malay dynasty ruling for over 660 years, forming one of the world's longest-lasting Muslim monarchies. Controlling much of Borneo during Sultan Bolkiah's era, Brunei survived as a small but wealthy independent state in the modern era through oil and natural gas riches after losing territory to Spanish and later British colonialism. Gaining full independence from Britain in 1984, Brunei is the only living example of Southeast Asia's Islamic monarchy tradition.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"4.94","capital_lon":"114.95","century_start":14,"century_end":21}}
